<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1894-02-07T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1894-02-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="553" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d553">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Uhl</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">White</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1894-02-07"><hi rend="italic">February 7,
                                1894</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 160.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of your
                            No. 184, of January, 1894 (day not given), and to approve your action in
                            issuing a passport to the minor, Joseph Wingfield, on the assumption
                            that his American birth and citizenship were established to your
                            satisfaction. In the case of a minor satisfactory proof of intent to
                            return to the United States before or on obtaining majority may be
                            accepted, even though the intended sojourn abroad may exceed two
                            years.</p>
                        <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Edwin F. Uhl</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Acting Secretary.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>